MACINTOSH SE

•	What year was it made? 
The Macintosh SE was released March 2, 1987. 
•	What operating system does it run? 
It supports and will run MAC OS 3.3–7.5.1 and 7.5.3–7.5.5.
•	How much did it cost (then and now, adjusted for inflation)? How hard is it to find one on the secondhand market (check eBay and Craig’s List). 
Originally it cost $2900 (dual floppy) and $3900 (with 20 MB hard drive). Today, those prices are $6074 and $8168, respectively.
•	In brief (a short paragraph), what were its historical strengths and weaknesses as a platform? What was it best known for?
The Macintosh SE was considered the 'low-end' of the Macintosh line and was mush less and the Macintosh II (at $5500 new), which came out in the same year. It had an internal drive bay, which could accomodate a 20MB or 40MB drive. It featured an expansion slot (SE stood for 'system expansion'), Used the Apple Desktop Bus (ADB) for keyboard and mouse control, included a cooling fan inside for active heat exchange, and claimed faster data throughput with improved SCSI support. While Apple rates SCSI on the SE at 1.25 MBps, users found that it reach approximately half of this speed. Moreover, the ROM was upgraded from 64kb to 256kb. Overall, the system is compact, includes ADB compatible keyboard and mice (now sold separately), and later SEs had a drive that supported high density floppy disks. The SE even supports color graphics, although not in the internal display! Still, it was this expansion slot that the SE remains best known for.

Turn it on (you must figure out how). Read some of Deena Larsen’s Marble Springs. Quit Marble Springs. What else is on this Mac?
I ran marble springs for a while, navigating around town. Then I quit marble springs, and loaded a copy of We Descend, by Bill Bly, which is located on the desktop. It is '895KB of text and graphics' and it takes quite a while to load up... Also, "Miss Sing" is on the desktop, among other files. 

===================================================================================================================
VECTREX

•	What year was it made? 
It was released in November, 1982.
•	What operating system does it run? 
The ROM within the Vectrex functions differently than traditional operating systems. Technically, Operating System is located at memory address $F000 to $FFFF. The system itself requires an input of some sort for functionality--when no cartridge is inserted, Space Invaders loads by default. When a cartridge is inserted, that game is immediately started by the OS that is embedded in the system's ROM. Besides the devolopmental floppy disks for software, there is not a way to access a text based form of the OS. Games could originally be programmed through CP/M systems with the Vectrex developmental software (requiring one floppy disk for Vectrex development, and another to store data). 
•	How much did it cost (then and now, adjusted for inflation)? How hard is it to find one on the secondhand market (check eBay and Craig’s List). 
When  released in November, 1982 it sold at a retail price of $199. Then, "the price dropped to $150 and then $100 shortly before the Video Game Crash of 1983." Now, that would be equivalent to $490, $370, and $246, respectively. Now, it appears that on ebay they're selling for about $175 to 200 in working condition, and for a bit more with games included. Games sell between about $10 and $50 a piece.
•	In brief (a short paragraph), what were its historical strengths and weaknesses as a platform? What was it best known for?
The Vectrex is the only vector-based home arcade system. The vectrex was unique in that it included its own built in monitor, (a vector monitor) and displayed vector graphics on this screen. Since many popular arcade games at the times used vector based graphics, after paying licensing fees, General Consumer Electronics was able to port and run many popular arcade titles of the time. It was best known for porting these popular vector graphics games. Also, it's strengths include the 'light pen,' when permitted feedback onscreen, and enabled one to 'draw' with select games and create vector based animations of their own.

Turn it on (you must figure out how). Play MineStorm. Try another cartridge. Why do you think the designer’s would have opted for the “vector” graphics?

I played a bit of Minestorm. It was pretty fun! I've played this game quite a bit before (at the MAL), but could only make it into level 2 this time. I really enjoy playing these games on vector graphics. I also played Star Trek (a show that I'm a fan of) and it was really fun. It's quite like Minestorm, except instead of playing as a 3rd person shooter, it's a first person shooter. Two thigs--the first is, this was a comparatively affordable setup, much more so than many of the systems on these tables. Also, the graphics are particularly responsive to fast-paced gameplay, very different from the systems up here as well. As I mentioned above, I believe the designers opted for Vector graphics in part, to license very popular vector-graphics based arcade games at the time. I'll also note that the response time on these fast paced games is excellent, and feels much quicker compared to a great many of the bitmapped graphics based games of the time.

===================================================================================================================
AMIGA

•	What year was it made? 
The Commodore Amiga was released in 1985.
•	What operating system does it run? 
The Commodore Amiga ran AmigaOS 1.0
•	How much did it cost (then and now, adjusted for inflation)? How hard is it to find one on the secondhand market (check eBay and Craig’s List). 
The base configuration with 256 KB of RAM was sold at a retail price of $1,295. In addition, "the 13-inch analog RGB monitor was available for around $300, bringing the price of a complete Amiga system to 1,595 USD." So,  the computer, monitor, and combined costs were, respectively, $2863, $663, and $3527. Even now, the Amiga is still fetching a price of ~$500 for a working model. They appear to be available, although in a bit limited quantity on sites such as Ebay.
•	In brief (a short paragraph), what were its historical strengths and weaknesses as a platform? What was it best known for?
The Amiga was, and is, considered a system that was far ahead of its time. It ran a very powerful "16/32-bit Motorola 68000 CPU" and contained "one of the most advanced graphics and sound systems in its class." In addition it "ran a preemptive multitasking operating system that fit into 512 KB of memory." The system was also released, and promoted by the likes of Andy Warhold, and was only sold in computer stores, in order to present it as a powerful and serious computing machine. Some sources, such have Byte magazine, have called it "the first multimedia computer" and PC World has called it the "7th greatest PC of all time." Clearly, it's influence and power was hugely significant in both home computing and entertainment. 

Turn it on (you must figure out how). Try the demos. What else can it do? (Hint: try the “Amiga Appetizer” disk). Have a look at the Amiga magazines and the book, The Future Was Here.

I turned the system on, palyed around a bit with first running kickstart, to run wordbench. I used the lines, dots, boxes, to see the color diversity and graphics capability and stability on the system. Then I ran the appetizers and played with the music editor, making a short song, but since there are no speakers connected, I was unable to output any sound. Still, the program was quite fun! Also, it was extremely easy to write a song on this system, and it was very intuitive and user friendly to do something so advanced (compared to the capabilities of computing peers of the time).

