MACINTOSH IIci

•	What year was it made? 
The Macintosh IIci was released on September 20th, 1989.
•	What operating system does it run? 
It supports Mac OS(s): 6.0.5; 6.0.7; 6.0.8; 7.0; 7.0.1; 7.1; 7.1.1 (Pro); 7.5; 6.0.4; 7.5.1; 7.5.3; 7.5.5; 7.6; 7.6.1
•	How much did it cost (then and now, adjusted for inflation)? How hard is it to find one on the secondhand market (check eBay and Craig’s List). 
The Macintosh IIci was originally sold for $6269. Now, it would sell for $12,029. Now, they appear to be selling for $60 to $100 shipped on ebay. I did not see any in the DC/Baltimore area on craiglist, but I would not be surprised if they appear. They seem to be widely available, in part I would guess because of their mass production for businesses, which likely resold many of these systems after use.
•	In brief (a short paragraph), what were its historical strengths and weaknesses as a platform? What was it best known for?
"The IIci was one of the most popular and longest lived Mac models of all time. For much of its lifespan, it was the business 'workhorse' of the Macintosh line." Moreo over, for a brief period in 1989 "before the introduction of the 40 MHz Macintosh IIfx, the IIci was the fastest Mac available." Not only was it a fast business machine, but it was powerful in part to support the transition from Mac OS 6 to Mac OS 7 (System 7). This was also the first 'non-all-in-one' Mac to include onboard graphics, which meant that another 'NuBus' slot was free--there were three of these slots open on the system. This permitted greater expansion, particularly useful in a powerhouse computer like this.

Turn it on (you must figure out how). Open WordPerfect. Open MS Word. Try typing a simple document in each. Which do you like better, and why? Open MacPaint. Try drawing something. (You don’t need to save any of your work from these applications.) What else is on this Mac? What can you learn about its past user(s)?

Both Wordperfect and MS word function MUCH more like our more contemporary word processing counterparts do. Very quick, easy to type on, MT keyboard (believe) has a much lighter response, so is easier to type quickly. The 'delete' button also permits a very quick correction, as opposed to use of error keys to either type over, or to arrow back and then press 'delete' to remove erroneous text. I admit, I find Word Perfect to be a bit nicer, perhaps becayse of its layour onscreen and the buttons available in the default layout, to work on the text. It seems (on face) easier to modify the draft layout on screen in Word perfect that in MS word. I also prefer the vertical cursor alone, that is default on Word PErfect to the additional horiztonal cursor in MS word. MS word also seems to have so many buttons up top, that the layout of the page is distorted and smaller than in Wordperfect. I've drawn some various lines in MacDraw. I've also used some of the patters to created patterned boxes and shapes across the screen. It's running hypercard, which as a very expensive piece of software. It also has the equivalent of hundreds of dollars worth of software on screen. This appears to have been owned by (and possibly still is) by UMD college park's library. There Nonprint media services, then in Hornbake's 4th floor, has a variety of files  onthe computer. Also, they have licensed much of the software on this system, which is additional reason for me to believe it has long been the propery of UMD libary's nonprint services. There are a variety of Nprint (Non print) folders on the hard rvie, with many iels that, upon opening, sort much of the hardware the is available at the university for internal use or for loan. 


